Today’s lecture focused on modern JavaScript (ES6) features, especially arrow functions and promises. These features help in writing cleaner, more efficient, and readable code. The mentor explained that arrow functions provide a shorter syntax for writing functions and do not have their own this context, which makes them useful in many situations.

Arrow functions use the => syntax and allow developers to write functions in a concise way. They are mainly used for small and simple operations. Compared to traditional functions, they reduce the amount of code and improve readability.

The session also introduced promises, which are used to handle asynchronous operations in JavaScript. A promise represents a value that may be available now, in the future, or never. Promises have three states: pending, fulfilled, and rejected. The mentor explained how .then() is used to handle successful results and .catch() is used to handle errors.

The working flow starts when an arrow function or promise is defined. In the case of promises, an asynchronous task is executed. If the operation is successful, the promise is fulfilled and .then() executes. If an error occurs, the promise is rejected and .catch() handles it. This helps in managing asynchronous code more effectively without blocking execution.

Understanding these concepts is important because modern JavaScript applications rely heavily on asynchronous programming and clean syntax.